# === memory-0792104d-0cd2-4fe8-90b0-7c836ae9519e ===
<urn:tesserai:twin:memory-0792104d-0cd2-4fe8-90b0-7c836ae9519e> <http://tesserai.io/ontology/createdAt> "2026-03-24T23:48:42.880098Z"^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#dateTime> ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/topics> "[\"Research Google Q4 2025 Earnings\",\"Search and analyze Google earnings data\",\"researcher\"]" ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/tool_name> "researcher" ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/structured_data> "null" ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/run_id> "ad1c0b95-d5b5-4b81-8bdc-47c8640c8942" ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/memory_type> "episodic" ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/created_at> "2026-03-24T23:48:42.879393+00:00" ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/content> "Here is the comprehensive research summary for Alphabet/Google's Q4 2025 earnings:\n\n---\n\n# Alphabet (GOOGL) Q4 2025 Earnings — Comprehensive Research Summary\n\n**Reported:** February 4, 2026 (after market close)\n\n---\n\n## 1. Financial Results\n\n| Metric | Actual | Estimate | Beat/Miss | YoY Change |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Total Revenue | $113.8B | $111.4B | **Beat +$2.4B** | +18% |\n| Diluted EPS | $2.82 | $2.61 | **Beat +8.1%** | +31% |\n| Net Income | $34.46B | — | — | +30% |\n| Operating Income | $35.93B | — | — | — |\n| Operating Margin | ~32% | — | — | Flat YoY |\n\n- **Full Year 2025 Revenue:** First-ever crossing of **$400 billion** ($400B+ annual)\n- **Full Year 2025 Net Income:** ~$132.2B (+15% YoY)\n\n---\n\n## 2. Segment Breakdown\n\n| Segment | Q4 2025 Revenue | Q4 2024 Revenue | YoY Growth |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Google Search & Other | $63.07B | $54.03B | **+17%** |\n| YouTube Ads | $11.38B | $10.47B | **+9%** |\n| Google Network | $7.8B | ~$7.95B | **-2%** |\n| Google Subscriptions/Platforms/Devices | $13.58B | $11.63B | **+17%** |\n| **Total Google Services** | **$95.9B** | — | **+14%** |\n| **Google Cloud** | **$17.66B** | **$11.96B** | **+48%** |\n| Other Bets | $370M | ~$400M | **-7.5%** |\n| **Total Advertising Revenue** | **$82.28B** | — | **+13.5%** |\n\n**Cloud profitability milestone:** Cloud operating income reached **$5.3B** (vs. $2.1B year-ago), operating margin just over **30%**. Cloud backlog more than doubled to **$240B annual run rate**. Full-year Cloud run rate exceeded **$70B**.\n\n**YouTube full-year:** YouTube (ads + subscriptions) exceeded **$60 billion** for all of 2025.\n\n---\n\n## 3. Key Highlights\n\n- **Search AI headwinds/tailwinds:** No evidence of Search cannibalization from Gemini app — AI Overviews and AI Mode are *expanding* overall query volume rather than replacing it.\n- **Cloud acceleration:** 48% growth in Q4 vs. 34% in Q3 — a notable re-acceleration. Outperformed Microsoft Azure growth for the first time in years (per DA Davidson).\n- **Gemini metrics:** 750M monthly active users on Gemini app; API throughput exceeds 10B tokens/minute; Gemini 3 launched as a \"major milestone\"; serving unit costs fell **78%** throughout 2025.\n- **AI in ads:** Hundreds of thousands of advertisers using AI Max; AI-generated code now constitutes ~50% of Google's internal codebase.\n- **Consumer subscriptions:** Exceeded **325 million** paid subscribers.\n- **Google Network miss:** The programmatic/display segment slipped -2%, continuing secular pressure on third-party ad networks.\n\n---\n\n## 4. Forward Guidance & AI Investment Plans\n\n- **2026 CapEx Guidance:** **$175B–$185B** — nearly double FY2025's ~$91.45B, and dramatically above Wall Street's expectation of ~$119.5B.\n  - ~60% allocated to servers; ~40% to data centers and networking\n  - Supply constraints expected to persist throughout 2026\n- **CFO Anat Ashkenazi** warned that depreciation expenses will **\"rise significantly\"** in Q1 2026 alongside infrastructure scaling.\n- **CEO Sundar Pichai:** Described maintaining \"a brutal pace to compete in AI\" and committed to \"a very, very relentless innovation cadence\" through 2026.\n- **Dividend:** Maintained at $0.21/share.\n\n---\n\n## 5. Stock Reaction\n\n| Timeframe | Movement |\n|---|---|\n| Immediate after-hours (Feb 4) | -7.5% initially, then recovered to ~-1.76% |\n| Peak intraday swing | ~$800B market cap fluctuation |\n| By February 19 | ~$302.58 (down from ~$340s post-earnings high) |\n| YTD context (Feb 2026) | Stock advanced from ~$190 (early 2025) to $300s |\n\nThe dominant driver of the sell-off was not earnings quality — it was **capex sticker shock**: the $175–185B guidance was ~$55–65B above consensus expectations.\n\n---\n\n## 6. Analyst Commentary\n\n| Firm | Rating | Previous Target | New Target | Key Note |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| J.P. Morgan | Overweight | $385 | **$395** | Better-than-expected revenue + EPS; 48% Cloud growth |\n| Goldman Sachs | Buy | $375 | **$400** | Cloud backlog growth; 48% vs. 40% forecast |\n| Bank of America | Buy | $335 | **$370** | \"Upside quarter\"; higher usage assumptions |\n| RBC Capital | Outperform | — | **$400** | Search strength; AI integration progress |\n| Wedbush | Outperform | $360 | **$370** | GenAI monetization in Gemini platform |\n| UBS | Neutral | $345 | **$348** | Balanced cloud/ad strength vs. capex + regulatory risks |\n\n**DA Davidson (Gil Luria):** Highlighted Google Cloud outperforming Microsoft Azure for the first time in years — justifies elevated spending.\n**Tim Ghriskey (Ingalls & Snyder):** Compared trajectory to Meta's 2022 \"Year of Efficiency\" pivot in reverse — aggressive spending accepted when growth is demonstrably strong.\n\n---\n\n## 7. Sector Impact\n\n### Ad Tech\n- Google's **+17% Search** and **+13.5% total ad revenue** growth validated the digital ad market's health and was broadly **bullish for META**.\n- **YouTube's +9% miss** (vs. higher expectations) introduced some nervousness around brand video budgets — modest headwind signal for **SNAP** and **YouTube-adjacent ad spend**.\n- **Google Network -2%** reinforced ongoing structural pressure on programmatic/open-web ad tech, a mild negative for **The Trade Desk (TTD)** and similar players.\n- The broader takeaway: ad spend is consolidating rapidly into **Alphabet, Amazon, and Meta**, leaving less incremental budget for the rest of the ecosystem.\n\n### Cloud Peers\n- Google Cloud's re-acceleration to **+48%** (vs. Azure at slower growth with Microsoft's capex concerns) was a **direct competitive signal**.\n- Microsoft had recently seen a 12% single-day stock drop when Azure decelerated despite high capex — Alphabet's opposite dynamic (acceleration + capex) created a **bifurcated cloud narrative**.\n- The capex magnitude ($175–185B) put pressure on **infrastructure/hyperscaler supply chains**: positive for **Nvidia, custom silicon, data center REITs**.\n\n### AI Sentiment\n- Gemini metrics (750M MAU, 78% cost reduction in serving) reinforced narrative that **AI cost curves are improving and usage is scaling**.\n- The massive capex commitment, while spooking near-term investors, was broadly interpreted as a signal that **AI demand is real and accelerating** — supportive for the AI infrastructure investment thesis.\n\n---\n\n**Sources:**\n- [Alphabet Q4 2025 Earnings — CNBC](https://www.cnbc.com/2026/02/04/alphabet-googl-q4-2025-earnings.html)\n- [Alphabet Reports Q4 2025 Revenue of $113.8 Billion — 9to5Google](https://9to5google.com/2026/02/04/alphabet-q4-2025-earnings/)\n- [Alphabet Q4 Highlights: Cloud +48%, YouTube Tops $60B — Finviz](https://finviz.com/news/300252/alphabet-q4-highlights-google-cloud-revenue-up-48-youtube-tops-60-billion-for-2025)\n- [Alphabet Outlines $175B–$185B 2026 CapEx Plan — Seeking Alpha](https://seekingalpha.com/news/4547610-alphabet-outlines-175b-185b-2026-capex-plan-as-ai-momentum-accelerates-across-search-cloud)\n- [Alphabet Resets the Bar for AI Infrastructure Spending — CNBC](https://www.cnbc.com/2026/02/04/alphabet-resets-the-bar-for-ai-infrastructure-spending.html)\n- [Alphabet Plans Record $185B AI Spending — Fortune](https://fortune.com/2026/02/04/alphabet-google-ai-spending-supply-constraints/)\n- [Alphabet Stock Forecast: Targets Lifted Following Q4 Results — Capital.com](https://capital.com/en-int/market-updates/alphabet-googl-stock-forecast-19-02-2026)\n- [Google Cloud Revenue Surges 48%, CapEx Guidance Nearly Doubles — TradingKey](https://www.tradingkey.com/analysis/stocks/us-stocks/261554176-google-goog-googl-stock-q4-earnings-cloud-capex-tradingkey)\n- [Alphabet Q4 FY 2025: Cloud Acceleration and Enterprise AI Momentum — Futurum Group](https://futurumgroup.com/insights/alphabet-q4-fy-2025-highlights-cloud-acceleration-and-enterprise-ai-momentum/)\n- [Strong Ad Growth Masks Investor Nerves Over Alphabet's AI Bill — WARC](https://www.warc.com/content/feed/google-q4-fy-2025-strong-ad-growth-masks-investor-nerves-over-alphabets-ai-bill/en-GB/11311)\n- [Alphabet Q4 2025 Earnings Press Release — SEC Filing](https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1652044/000165204426000012/googexhibit991q42025.htm)\n- [Alphabet CEO Q4 2025 Remarks — Google Blog](https://blog.google/company-news/inside-google/message-ceo/alphabet-earnings-q4-2025/)" ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/confidence> "1"^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#double> ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/agent_id> "0fe3fc03-ac5f-4f6a-bd35-798a2d5d39d0" ;
	<http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment> "Here is the comprehensive research summary for Alphabet/Google's Q4 2025 earnings:\n\n---\n\n# Alphabet (GOOGL) Q4 2025 Earnings — Comprehensive Research Summary\n\n**Reported:** February 4, 2026 (after market close)\n\n---\n\n## 1. Financial Results\n\n| Metric | Actual | Estimate | Beat/Miss | YoY Change |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Total Revenue | $113.8B | $111.4B | **Beat +$2.4B** | +18% |\n| Diluted EPS | $2.82 | $2.61 | **Beat +8.1%** | +31% |\n| Net Income | $34.46B | — | — | +30% |\n| Operating Income | $35.93B | — | — | — |\n| Operating Margin | ~32% | — | — | Flat YoY |\n\n- **Full Year 2025 Revenue:** First-ever crossing of **$400 billion** ($400B+ annual)\n- **Full Year 2025 Net Income:** ~$132.2B (+15% YoY)\n\n---\n\n## 2. Segment Breakdown\n\n| Segment | Q4 2025 Revenue | Q4 2024 Revenue | YoY Growth |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Google Search & Other | $63.07B | $54.03B | **+17%** |\n| YouTube Ads | $11.38B | $10.47B | **+9%** |\n| Google Network | $7.8B | ~$7.95B | **-2%** |\n| Google Subscriptions/Platforms/Devices | $13.58B | $11.63B | **+17%** |\n| **Total Google Services** | **$95.9B** | — | **+14%** |\n| **Google Cloud** | **$17.66B** | **$11.96B** | **+48%** |\n| Other Bets | $370M | ~$400M | **-7.5%** |\n| **Total Advertising Revenue** | **$82.28B** | — | **+13.5%** |\n\n**Cloud profitability milestone:** Cloud operating income reached **$5.3B** (vs. $2.1B year-ago), operating margin just over **30%**. Cloud backlog more than doubled to **$240B annual run rate**. Full-year Cloud run rate exceeded **$70B**.\n\n**YouTube full-year:** YouTube (ads + subscriptions) exceeded **$60 billion** for all of 2025.\n\n---\n\n## 3. Key Highlights\n\n- **Search AI headwinds/tailwinds:** No evidence of Search cannibalization from Gemini app — AI Overviews and AI Mode are *expanding* overall query volume rather than replacing it.\n- **Cloud acceleration:** 48% growth in Q4 vs. 34% in Q3 — a notable re-acceleration. Outperformed Microsoft Azure growth for the first time in years (per DA Davidson).\n- **Gemini metrics:** 750M monthly active users on Gemini app; API throughput exceeds 10B tokens/minute; Gemini 3 launched as a \"major milestone\"; serving unit costs fell **78%** throughout 2025.\n- **AI in ads:** Hundreds of thousands of advertisers using AI Max; AI-generated code now constitutes ~50% of Google's internal codebase.\n- **Consumer subscriptions:** Exceeded **325 million** paid subscribers.\n- **Google Network miss:** The programmatic/display segment slipped -2%, continuing secular pressure on third-party ad networks.\n\n---\n\n## 4. Forward Guidance & AI Investment Plans\n\n- **2026 CapEx Guidance:** **$175B–$185B** — nearly double FY2025's ~$91.45B, and dramatically above Wall Street's expectation of ~$119.5B.\n  - ~60% allocated to servers; ~40% to data centers and networking\n  - Supply constraints expected to persist throughout 2026\n- **CFO Anat Ashkenazi** warned that depreciation expenses will **\"rise significantly\"** in Q1 2026 alongside infrastructure scaling.\n- **CEO Sundar Pichai:** Described maintaining \"a brutal pace to compete in AI\" and committed to \"a very, very relentless innovation cadence\" through 2026.\n- **Dividend:** Maintained at $0.21/share.\n\n---\n\n## 5. Stock Reaction\n\n| Timeframe | Movement |\n|---|---|\n| Immediate after-hours (Feb 4) | -7.5% initially, then recovered to ~-1.76% |\n| Peak intraday swing | ~$800B market cap fluctuation |\n| By February 19 | ~$302.58 (down from ~$340s post-earnings high) |\n| YTD context (Feb 2026) | Stock advanced from ~$190 (early 2025) to $300s |\n\nThe dominant driver of the sell-off was not earnings quality — it was **capex sticker shock**: the $175–185B guidance was ~$55–65B above consensus expectations.\n\n---\n\n## 6. Analyst Commentary\n\n| Firm | Rating | Previous Target | New Target | Key Note |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| J.P. Morgan | Overweight | $385 | **$395** | Better-than-expected revenue + EPS; 48% Cloud growth |\n| Goldman Sachs | Buy | $375 | **$400** | Cloud backlog growth; 48% vs. 40% forecast |\n| Bank of America | Buy | $335 | **$370** | \"Upside quarter\"; higher usage assumptions |\n| RBC Capital | Outperform | — | **$400** | Search strength; AI integration progress |\n| Wedbush | Outperform | $360 | **$370** | GenAI monetization in Gemini platform |\n| UBS | Neutral | $345 | **$348** | Balanced cloud/ad strength vs. capex + regulatory risks |\n\n**DA Davidson (Gil Luria):** Highlighted Google Cloud outperforming Microsoft Azure for the first time in years — justifies elevated spending.\n**Tim Ghriskey (Ingalls & Snyder):** Compared trajectory to Meta's 2022 \"Year of Efficiency\" pivot in reverse — aggressive spending accepted when growth is demonstrably strong.\n\n---\n\n## 7. Sector Impact\n\n### Ad Tech\n- Google's **+17% Search** and **+13.5% total ad revenue** growth validated the digital ad market's health and was broadly **bullish for META**.\n- **YouTube's +9% miss** (vs. higher expectations) introduced some nervousness around brand video budgets — modest headwind signal for **SNAP** and **YouTube-adjacent ad spend**.\n- **Google Network -2%** reinforced ongoing structural pressure on programmatic/open-web ad tech, a mild negative for **The Trade Desk (TTD)** and similar players.\n- The broader takeaway: ad spend is consolidating rapidly into **Alphabet, Amazon, and Meta**, leaving less incremental budget for the rest of the ecosystem.\n\n### Cloud Peers\n- Google Cloud's re-acceleration to **+48%** (vs. Azure at slower growth with Microsoft's capex concerns) was a **direct competitive signal**.\n- Microsoft had recently seen a 12% single-day stock drop when Azure decelerated despite high capex — Alphabet's opposite dynamic (acceleration + capex) created a **bifurcated cloud narrative**.\n- The capex magnitude ($175–185B) put pressure on **infrastructure/hyperscaler supply chains**: positive for **Nvidia, custom silicon, data center REITs**.\n\n### AI Sentiment\n- Gemini metrics (750M MAU, 78% cost reduction in serving) reinforced narrative that **AI cost curves are improving and usage is scaling**.\n- The massive capex commitment, while spooking near-term investors, was broadly interpreted as a signal that **AI demand is real and accelerating** — supportive for the AI infrastructure investment thesis.\n\n---\n\n**Sources:**\n- [Alphabet Q4 2025 Earnings — CNBC](https://www.cnbc.com/2026/02/04/alphabet-googl-q4-2025-earnings.html)\n- [Alphabet Reports Q4 2025 Revenue of $113.8 Billion — 9to5Google](https://9to5google.com/2026/02/04/alphabet-q4-2025-earnings/)\n- [Alphabet Q4 Highlights: Cloud +48%, YouTube Tops $60B — Finviz](https://finviz.com/news/300252/alphabet-q4-highlights-google-cloud-revenue-up-48-youtube-tops-60-billion-for-2025)\n- [Alphabet Outlines $175B–$185B 2026 CapEx Plan — Seeking Alpha](https://seekingalpha.com/news/4547610-alphabet-outlines-175b-185b-2026-capex-plan-as-ai-momentum-accelerates-across-search-cloud)\n- [Alphabet Resets the Bar for AI Infrastructure Spending — CNBC](https://www.cnbc.com/2026/02/04/alphabet-resets-the-bar-for-ai-infrastructure-spending.html)\n- [Alphabet Plans Record $185B AI Spending — Fortune](https://fortune.com/2026/02/04/alphabet-google-ai-spending-supply-constraints/)\n- [Alphabet Stock Forecast: Targets Lifted Following Q4 Results — Capital.com](https://capital.com/en-int/market-updates/alphabet-googl-stock-forecast-19-02-2026)\n- [Google Cloud Revenue Surges 48%, CapEx Guidance Nearly Doubles — TradingKey](https://www.tradingkey.com/analysis/stocks/us-stocks/261554176-google-goog-googl-stock-q4-earnings-cloud-capex-tradingkey)\n- [Alphabet Q4 FY 2025: Cloud Acceleration and Enterprise AI Momentum — Futurum Group](https://futurumgroup.com/insights/alphabet-q4-fy-2025-highlights-cloud-acceleration-and-enterprise-ai-momentum/)\n- [Strong Ad Growth Masks Investor Nerves Over Alphabet's AI Bill — WARC](https://www.warc.com/content/feed/google-q4-fy-2025-strong-ad-growth-masks-investor-nerves-over-alphabets-ai-bill/en-GB/11311)\n- [Alphabet Q4 2025 Earnings Press Release — SEC Filing](https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1652044/000165204426000012/googexhibit991q42025.htm)\n- [Alphabet CEO Q4 2025 Remarks — Google Blog](https://blog.google/company-news/inside-google/message-ceo/alphabet-earnings-q4-2025/)" ;
	<http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "[researcher] Here is the comprehensive research summary for Alphabet/Google's Q4 2025 earning" ;
	a <https://schema.org/EpisodicMemory> .


