# === memory-0f1ba5c1-7d12-4773-b812-65a7b25380b9 ===
<urn:tesserai:twin:memory-0f1ba5c1-7d12-4773-b812-65a7b25380b9> <http://tesserai.io/ontology/createdAt> "2026-03-24T23:57:30.610619Z"^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#dateTime> ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/topics> "[\"Research Semiconductor Sector Impact\",\"Research semiconductor sector reaction\",\"researcher\"]" ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/tool_name> "researcher" ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/structured_data> "null" ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/run_id> "ad1c0b95-d5b5-4b81-8bdc-47c8640c8942" ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/memory_type> "episodic" ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/created_at> "2026-03-24T23:57:30.609857+00:00" ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/content> "Here is the compiled research on how Q4 2025 big tech earnings affected the semiconductor sector:\n\n---\n\n## Semiconductor Sector: Reaction to Q4 2025 Big Tech Earnings\n\n### 1. Sector-Wide Reaction — SOX, SMH, SOXX\n\n**Semiconductors entered 2026 on strong footing.** The Philadelphia Semiconductor Index (SOX) rallied ~4% in the first week of January 2026 alongside a broader chip stock surge. The VanEck Semiconductor ETF (SMH) built on a ~49% gain in 2025. SOX reached a 52-week high of **8,498.10** on February 25, 2026, marking a 52% one-year gain.\n\nKey catalysts during earnings season (late January–early February 2026):\n- **Alphabet and Amazon raised 2026 capex forecasts** during their Q4 calls, triggering immediate rallies in Nvidia, Broadcom, and TSM shares.\n- **TSMC's January 2026 revenue** jumped 36.8% YoY (to NT$401.3B / ~$12.7B), signaling AI demand was sustaining well above full-year guidance of ~30%.\n- **Micron HBM4 shipments** announced in February sparked a global rally — Micron +10%, Samsung and SK Hynix up sharply.\n\n---\n\n### 2. Key Stock Movements\n\n| Company | Q4 2025 / Early 2026 Performance | Key Driver |\n|---|---|---|\n| **NVIDIA** | +5% YTD by Feb 2026; Q4 FY26 revenue $68.1B (+73% YoY) | Data center revenue $62B; cloud GPU sold out; hyperscaler capex |\n| **TSMC** | New 52-week high ($365.60) Feb 2026; Jan revenue +37% | Apple iPhone demand + AI chip production (Apple A-series, NVIDIA Blackwell) |\n| **AMD** | +1.8% after-hours on Q4 beat (Feb 3, 2026); FY2025 revenue $34.6B (+34%) | Record data center revenue; EPYC + Instinct GPU demand |\n| **Broadcom** | Stock up 75% in 2025; Q4 FY2025 revenue $18B (+28% YoY) | Custom AI accelerators; AI revenue guided to double YoY to $8.2B in Q1 2026 |\n| **Qualcomm** | Underperformed (−19.85% over year); facing Apple modem loss | Apple C1 modem launch in Feb 2026 ending Qualcomm dependence |\n| **Intel** | Q4 revenue $13.7B (−4% YoY); worst full-year since 2010 ($52.9B) | Foundry losses ($2.5B operating loss Q4); misjudged data center CPU demand |\n| **Micron** | +10% rally Feb 12, 2026; champion of SOX (+309% over year) | HBM4 mass production; AI memory demand, SK Hynix booked out through 2026 |\n\n---\n\n### 3. AI Chip Demand — Cloud Capex Read-Through\n\nBig tech Q4 2025 earnings revealed **historically high and accelerating cloud capex**, which was the strongest direct signal for AI accelerator demand:\n\n| Company | Q4 2025 Cloud Revenue | 2026 Capex Guidance |\n|---|---|---|\n| **AWS (Amazon)** | $35.6B (+24% YoY — highest growth in 3+ years) | ~$200B |\n| **Google Cloud (Alphabet)** | $17.7B (+48% YoY) | $175–185B |\n| **Microsoft Azure** | +39% YoY | ~$120B+ |\n| **Meta** | — | $115–135B |\n\n**Combined 2026 capex commitment from the Big Five hyperscalers: $660–690B** — nearly double 2025 levels, with ~75% ($450B+) directed at AI infrastructure.\n\n- Hyperscalers accounted for **>50% of NVIDIA's data center revenue**\n- NVIDIA CEO Jensen Huang: *\"Blackwell sales are off the charts, and cloud GPUs are sold out\"*\n- All hyperscalers described their markets as **supply-constrained, not demand-constrained**\n- BofA total AI capex estimate for 2026: **$432B**, with Nvidia and Broadcom as top picks\n\n---\n\n### 4. Consumer Chip Demand — Apple Signals\n\nApple Q4 2025 (calendar Q4, reported October 2025):\n- **Total revenue: $102.5B** (+7.9% YoY, record)\n- **iPhone revenue: $49B** (+6% YoY); full holiday quarter record of $85.3B for the fiscal quarter\n\nImpact on consumer-facing chipmakers:\n- **TSMC**: Directly benefited; Apple is TSMC's largest customer; Q4 2025 revenue +20.5% YoY, with advanced nodes (7nm and below) at 74% of wafer revenue\n- **TSMC Q1 2026 guidance**: $34.6–35.8B (+38% YoY) — partly reflecting Apple iPhone demand ramp\n- **Qualcomm**: Negative signal — Apple launched its **in-house C1 modem** in February 2026, beginning the end of Qualcomm's modem relationship with Apple (full exit expected by 2027). Qualcomm was the weakest SOX component (−19.85% over the year).\n\n---\n\n### 5. Supply Chain — Lead Times, Inventory, Capacity\n\n- **AI memory (HBM, DDR5)**: Tight supply extending into 2026. SK Hynix had its entire memory chip capacity **booked through 2026**. DDR5 supply tightening due to AI data center buildout.\n- **TSMC capacity**: Fully subscribed for advanced nodes; 2026 capex guided at **$52–56B**, its highest ever, reflecting sustained demand visibility.\n- **Intel**: Ironically supply-constrained on Xeon processors — demand for data center CPUs exceeded supply, driven by AI infrastructure. Supply relief expected by Q2 2026 as Intel invests in internal wafer capacity.\n- **Certain analog/automotive chips** (TCAN series, LDOs, isolators): Lead times extending to **20 weeks**.\n- **Semiconductor manufacturing sector collectively**: 14 tracked stocks beat Q4 2025 revenue estimates by ~3% collectively. Marvell inventory rose slightly; Teradyne saw significant inventory improvement.\n\n---\n\n### 6. Forward Outlook — How Big Tech Guidance Shifted Semiconductor Expectations\n\n1. **Demand floor established**: The coordinated capex ramp by all hyperscalers removed near-term demand uncertainty for AI chips. Analysts at BofA kept Nvidia and Broadcom as top picks; Mizuho projected Broadcom AI revenue growing 103% YoY to $40.4B in FY2026.\n2. **NVIDIA's own Q4 FY26 (Feb 25, 2026)**: Revenue $68.1B (+73% YoY); Q1 FY27 guidance of **$78B** — quashing AI bubble concerns. Stock dipped ~5% post-earnings on \"priced-in\" valuation concerns despite the beat.\n3. **Semiconductor spending trajectory**: Wall Street analysts projected semiconductor spending hitting **$1 trillion in 2026**, with AI infrastructure as primary driver.\n4. **Divergence in sector**: Clear split between AI/data center winners (Nvidia, Broadcom, TSMC, AMD, Micron) and consumer/PC laggards (Intel, Qualcomm). Consumer segments showed modest recovery while AI remained the dominant growth engine.\n5. **TSMC positioned as key beneficiary**: Both Apple consumer demand and AI accelerator production concentrated at TSMC advanced nodes (N3, N2).\n\n---\n\n### Summary: Causal Chain\n\n```\nBig Tech Q4 2025 Earnings\n    ├── AWS/Azure/GCP cloud re-acceleration (+24–48% YoY)\n    ├── Hyperscaler 2026 capex guidance $660–690B combined\n    │       └── → NVIDIA/AMD/Broadcom: AI chip demand confirmed, stocks rally\n    ├── Apple iPhone record quarter + C1 modem launch\n    │       ├── → TSMC: Strong demand, Jan revenue +37%, new ATH\n    │       └── → Qualcomm: Bearish signal, modem revenue at risk\n    └── Intel: Missed AI transition, supply-constrained on Xeon,\n               foundry $10B annual loss — underperformed sector\n```\n\n---\n\n**Sources:**\n- [Chip stocks rally to start 2026 — CNBC](https://www.cnbc.com/2026/01/02/chipmakers-2026-ai-trade.html)\n- [TSMC Revenue Jumps 37% in January — Bloomberg](https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2026-02-10/tsmc-revenue-jumps-37-in-january-while-ai-spending-marches-on)\n- [TSMC Q4 FY2025 Results and 2026 Outlook — Futurum](https://futurumgroup.com/insights/tsmc-q4-fy-2025-results-and-fy-2026-outlook-signal-ai-led-growth/)\n- [TSMC Q4 2025 Quarterly Results](https://investor.tsmc.com/english/quarterly-results/2025/q4)\n- [Nvidia Q4 FY2026 Earnings: $68B Revenue — CNBC](https://www.cnbc.com/2026/02/25/nvidia-nvda-earnings-report-q4-2026.html)\n- [Nvidia smashes Q4 2026 with $68B — Fortune](https://fortune.com/2026/02/25/nvidia-nvda-earnings-record-capex-spend-ai/)\n- [AMD Q4 2025 Record Revenue — Investing.com](https://www.investing.com/news/company-news/amd-q4-2025-slides-record-revenue-and-earnings-as-ai-demand-surges-93CH-4483422)\n- [Broadcom Q4 FY2025 Earnings — Futurum](https://futurumgroup.com/insights/broadcom-q4-fy-2025-earnings-ai-and-software-drive-beat/)\n- [Intel Q4 2025: Rocky Path to Recovery — Tom's Hardware](https://www.tomshardware.com/pc-components/cpus/intel-q4-earnings-reveal-rocky-path-to-recovery-following-weakest-full-year-revenue-since-2010-intel-foundry-losses-continue-as-18a-begins-ramp-but-supply-challenges-set-to-ease-in-q2-2026)\n- [Intel $600M Net Loss in Q4 2025 — DCD](https://www.datacenterdynamics.com/en/news/intel-reports-600m-net-loss-in-q4-2025-admits-to-misjudging-data-center-cpu-demand/)\n- [Google Cloud Leads Q4 2025 Growth — Windows Forum](https://windowsforum.com/threads/google-cloud-leads-q4-2025-growth-amid-capex-surge-and-capacity-constraints.402503/)\n- [AI Capex 2026: $690B Infrastructure Sprint — Futurum](https://futurumgroup.com/insights/ai-capex-2026-the-690b-infrastructure-sprint/)\n- [Micron Sparks Global Semiconductor Rally 2026 — Evrimagaci](https://evrimagaci.org/gpt/micron-sparks-global-semiconductor-stock-rally-in-2026-528512)\n- [Semiconductors Winners and Losers Start of 2026 — Seeking Alpha](https://seekingalpha.com/article/4857310-semiconductors-winners-and-losers-at-the-start-of-2026)\n- [Apple Q4 2025: Record $102.5B Revenue — The Acquirer's Multiple](https://acquirersmultiple.com/2025/11/apple-q4-2025-record-102-5b-revenue-surging-services-and-ai-powered-future/)\n- [Apple's chip partner TSMC driven to new heights — AppleInsider](https://appleinsider.com/articles/26/01/09/apples-chip-partner-tsmc-revenue-driven-to-new-heights-by-iphone-ai)\n- [Big Tech Will Spend $600B on AI in 2026 — Investing.com](https://www.investing.com/analysis/big-tech-will-spend-600b-on-ai-in-2026-5-stocks-cashing-the-checks-200674615)\n- [2026 Semiconductor Industry Market Outlook — Sourceability](https://sourceability.com/post/whats-ahead-in-2026-for-the-semiconductor-industry)" ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/confidence> "1"^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#double> ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/agent_id> "fe530c5e-5197-4c45-affd-41b68166e875" ;
	<http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment> "Here is the compiled research on how Q4 2025 big tech earnings affected the semiconductor sector:\n\n---\n\n## Semiconductor Sector: Reaction to Q4 2025 Big Tech Earnings\n\n### 1. Sector-Wide Reaction — SOX, SMH, SOXX\n\n**Semiconductors entered 2026 on strong footing.** The Philadelphia Semiconductor Index (SOX) rallied ~4% in the first week of January 2026 alongside a broader chip stock surge. The VanEck Semiconductor ETF (SMH) built on a ~49% gain in 2025. SOX reached a 52-week high of **8,498.10** on February 25, 2026, marking a 52% one-year gain.\n\nKey catalysts during earnings season (late January–early February 2026):\n- **Alphabet and Amazon raised 2026 capex forecasts** during their Q4 calls, triggering immediate rallies in Nvidia, Broadcom, and TSM shares.\n- **TSMC's January 2026 revenue** jumped 36.8% YoY (to NT$401.3B / ~$12.7B), signaling AI demand was sustaining well above full-year guidance of ~30%.\n- **Micron HBM4 shipments** announced in February sparked a global rally — Micron +10%, Samsung and SK Hynix up sharply.\n\n---\n\n### 2. Key Stock Movements\n\n| Company | Q4 2025 / Early 2026 Performance | Key Driver |\n|---|---|---|\n| **NVIDIA** | +5% YTD by Feb 2026; Q4 FY26 revenue $68.1B (+73% YoY) | Data center revenue $62B; cloud GPU sold out; hyperscaler capex |\n| **TSMC** | New 52-week high ($365.60) Feb 2026; Jan revenue +37% | Apple iPhone demand + AI chip production (Apple A-series, NVIDIA Blackwell) |\n| **AMD** | +1.8% after-hours on Q4 beat (Feb 3, 2026); FY2025 revenue $34.6B (+34%) | Record data center revenue; EPYC + Instinct GPU demand |\n| **Broadcom** | Stock up 75% in 2025; Q4 FY2025 revenue $18B (+28% YoY) | Custom AI accelerators; AI revenue guided to double YoY to $8.2B in Q1 2026 |\n| **Qualcomm** | Underperformed (−19.85% over year); facing Apple modem loss | Apple C1 modem launch in Feb 2026 ending Qualcomm dependence |\n| **Intel** | Q4 revenue $13.7B (−4% YoY); worst full-year since 2010 ($52.9B) | Foundry losses ($2.5B operating loss Q4); misjudged data center CPU demand |\n| **Micron** | +10% rally Feb 12, 2026; champion of SOX (+309% over year) | HBM4 mass production; AI memory demand, SK Hynix booked out through 2026 |\n\n---\n\n### 3. AI Chip Demand — Cloud Capex Read-Through\n\nBig tech Q4 2025 earnings revealed **historically high and accelerating cloud capex**, which was the strongest direct signal for AI accelerator demand:\n\n| Company | Q4 2025 Cloud Revenue | 2026 Capex Guidance |\n|---|---|---|\n| **AWS (Amazon)** | $35.6B (+24% YoY — highest growth in 3+ years) | ~$200B |\n| **Google Cloud (Alphabet)** | $17.7B (+48% YoY) | $175–185B |\n| **Microsoft Azure** | +39% YoY | ~$120B+ |\n| **Meta** | — | $115–135B |\n\n**Combined 2026 capex commitment from the Big Five hyperscalers: $660–690B** — nearly double 2025 levels, with ~75% ($450B+) directed at AI infrastructure.\n\n- Hyperscalers accounted for **>50% of NVIDIA's data center revenue**\n- NVIDIA CEO Jensen Huang: *\"Blackwell sales are off the charts, and cloud GPUs are sold out\"*\n- All hyperscalers described their markets as **supply-constrained, not demand-constrained**\n- BofA total AI capex estimate for 2026: **$432B**, with Nvidia and Broadcom as top picks\n\n---\n\n### 4. Consumer Chip Demand — Apple Signals\n\nApple Q4 2025 (calendar Q4, reported October 2025):\n- **Total revenue: $102.5B** (+7.9% YoY, record)\n- **iPhone revenue: $49B** (+6% YoY); full holiday quarter record of $85.3B for the fiscal quarter\n\nImpact on consumer-facing chipmakers:\n- **TSMC**: Directly benefited; Apple is TSMC's largest customer; Q4 2025 revenue +20.5% YoY, with advanced nodes (7nm and below) at 74% of wafer revenue\n- **TSMC Q1 2026 guidance**: $34.6–35.8B (+38% YoY) — partly reflecting Apple iPhone demand ramp\n- **Qualcomm**: Negative signal — Apple launched its **in-house C1 modem** in February 2026, beginning the end of Qualcomm's modem relationship with Apple (full exit expected by 2027). Qualcomm was the weakest SOX component (−19.85% over the year).\n\n---\n\n### 5. Supply Chain — Lead Times, Inventory, Capacity\n\n- **AI memory (HBM, DDR5)**: Tight supply extending into 2026. SK Hynix had its entire memory chip capacity **booked through 2026**. DDR5 supply tightening due to AI data center buildout.\n- **TSMC capacity**: Fully subscribed for advanced nodes; 2026 capex guided at **$52–56B**, its highest ever, reflecting sustained demand visibility.\n- **Intel**: Ironically supply-constrained on Xeon processors — demand for data center CPUs exceeded supply, driven by AI infrastructure. Supply relief expected by Q2 2026 as Intel invests in internal wafer capacity.\n- **Certain analog/automotive chips** (TCAN series, LDOs, isolators): Lead times extending to **20 weeks**.\n- **Semiconductor manufacturing sector collectively**: 14 tracked stocks beat Q4 2025 revenue estimates by ~3% collectively. Marvell inventory rose slightly; Teradyne saw significant inventory improvement.\n\n---\n\n### 6. Forward Outlook — How Big Tech Guidance Shifted Semiconductor Expectations\n\n1. **Demand floor established**: The coordinated capex ramp by all hyperscalers removed near-term demand uncertainty for AI chips. Analysts at BofA kept Nvidia and Broadcom as top picks; Mizuho projected Broadcom AI revenue growing 103% YoY to $40.4B in FY2026.\n2. **NVIDIA's own Q4 FY26 (Feb 25, 2026)**: Revenue $68.1B (+73% YoY); Q1 FY27 guidance of **$78B** — quashing AI bubble concerns. Stock dipped ~5% post-earnings on \"priced-in\" valuation concerns despite the beat.\n3. **Semiconductor spending trajectory**: Wall Street analysts projected semiconductor spending hitting **$1 trillion in 2026**, with AI infrastructure as primary driver.\n4. **Divergence in sector**: Clear split between AI/data center winners (Nvidia, Broadcom, TSMC, AMD, Micron) and consumer/PC laggards (Intel, Qualcomm). Consumer segments showed modest recovery while AI remained the dominant growth engine.\n5. **TSMC positioned as key beneficiary**: Both Apple consumer demand and AI accelerator production concentrated at TSMC advanced nodes (N3, N2).\n\n---\n\n### Summary: Causal Chain\n\n```\nBig Tech Q4 2025 Earnings\n    ├── AWS/Azure/GCP cloud re-acceleration (+24–48% YoY)\n    ├── Hyperscaler 2026 capex guidance $660–690B combined\n    │       └── → NVIDIA/AMD/Broadcom: AI chip demand confirmed, stocks rally\n    ├── Apple iPhone record quarter + C1 modem launch\n    │       ├── → TSMC: Strong demand, Jan revenue +37%, new ATH\n    │       └── → Qualcomm: Bearish signal, modem revenue at risk\n    └── Intel: Missed AI transition, supply-constrained on Xeon,\n               foundry $10B annual loss — underperformed sector\n```\n\n---\n\n**Sources:**\n- [Chip stocks rally to start 2026 — CNBC](https://www.cnbc.com/2026/01/02/chipmakers-2026-ai-trade.html)\n- [TSMC Revenue Jumps 37% in January — Bloomberg](https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2026-02-10/tsmc-revenue-jumps-37-in-january-while-ai-spending-marches-on)\n- [TSMC Q4 FY2025 Results and 2026 Outlook — Futurum](https://futurumgroup.com/insights/tsmc-q4-fy-2025-results-and-fy-2026-outlook-signal-ai-led-growth/)\n- [TSMC Q4 2025 Quarterly Results](https://investor.tsmc.com/english/quarterly-results/2025/q4)\n- [Nvidia Q4 FY2026 Earnings: $68B Revenue — CNBC](https://www.cnbc.com/2026/02/25/nvidia-nvda-earnings-report-q4-2026.html)\n- [Nvidia smashes Q4 2026 with $68B — Fortune](https://fortune.com/2026/02/25/nvidia-nvda-earnings-record-capex-spend-ai/)\n- [AMD Q4 2025 Record Revenue — Investing.com](https://www.investing.com/news/company-news/amd-q4-2025-slides-record-revenue-and-earnings-as-ai-demand-surges-93CH-4483422)\n- [Broadcom Q4 FY2025 Earnings — Futurum](https://futurumgroup.com/insights/broadcom-q4-fy-2025-earnings-ai-and-software-drive-beat/)\n- [Intel Q4 2025: Rocky Path to Recovery — Tom's Hardware](https://www.tomshardware.com/pc-components/cpus/intel-q4-earnings-reveal-rocky-path-to-recovery-following-weakest-full-year-revenue-since-2010-intel-foundry-losses-continue-as-18a-begins-ramp-but-supply-challenges-set-to-ease-in-q2-2026)\n- [Intel $600M Net Loss in Q4 2025 — DCD](https://www.datacenterdynamics.com/en/news/intel-reports-600m-net-loss-in-q4-2025-admits-to-misjudging-data-center-cpu-demand/)\n- [Google Cloud Leads Q4 2025 Growth — Windows Forum](https://windowsforum.com/threads/google-cloud-leads-q4-2025-growth-amid-capex-surge-and-capacity-constraints.402503/)\n- [AI Capex 2026: $690B Infrastructure Sprint — Futurum](https://futurumgroup.com/insights/ai-capex-2026-the-690b-infrastructure-sprint/)\n- [Micron Sparks Global Semiconductor Rally 2026 — Evrimagaci](https://evrimagaci.org/gpt/micron-sparks-global-semiconductor-stock-rally-in-2026-528512)\n- [Semiconductors Winners and Losers Start of 2026 — Seeking Alpha](https://seekingalpha.com/article/4857310-semiconductors-winners-and-losers-at-the-start-of-2026)\n- [Apple Q4 2025: Record $102.5B Revenue — The Acquirer's Multiple](https://acquirersmultiple.com/2025/11/apple-q4-2025-record-102-5b-revenue-surging-services-and-ai-powered-future/)\n- [Apple's chip partner TSMC driven to new heights — AppleInsider](https://appleinsider.com/articles/26/01/09/apples-chip-partner-tsmc-revenue-driven-to-new-heights-by-iphone-ai)\n- [Big Tech Will Spend $600B on AI in 2026 — Investing.com](https://www.investing.com/analysis/big-tech-will-spend-600b-on-ai-in-2026-5-stocks-cashing-the-checks-200674615)\n- [2026 Semiconductor Industry Market Outlook — Sourceability](https://sourceability.com/post/whats-ahead-in-2026-for-the-semiconductor-industry)" ;
	<http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "[researcher] Here is the compiled research on how Q4 2025 big tech earnings affected the semi" ;
	a <https://schema.org/EpisodicMemory> .


