# === memory-45a9ada3-d6eb-4601-8c68-652265d438c1 ===
<urn:tesserai:twin:memory-45a9ada3-d6eb-4601-8c68-652265d438c1> <http://tesserai.io/ontology/createdAt> "2026-03-24T23:44:14.732633Z"^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#dateTime> ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/topics> "[\"Research Apple Q4 2025 Earnings\",\"Search and analyze Apple earnings data\",\"researcher\"]" ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/tool_name> "researcher" ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/structured_data> "null" ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/run_id> "ad1c0b95-d5b5-4b81-8bdc-47c8640c8942" ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/memory_type> "episodic" ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/created_at> "2026-03-24T23:44:14.731966+00:00" ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/content> "Here is the comprehensive summary of Apple's fiscal Q1 2026 (calendar Q4 2025) earnings:\n\n---\n\n## Apple Fiscal Q1 2026 Earnings — Comprehensive Summary\n**Reported: January 29, 2026 | Period: October–December 2025**\n\n---\n\n### 1. Financial Results\n\n| Metric | Actual | Analyst Estimate | Beat/Miss | YoY Change |\n|--------|--------|-----------------|-----------|------------|\n| Revenue | **$143.8B** | $138.48B | +$5.3B beat | **+16%** |\n| EPS (diluted) | **$2.84** | $2.67 | +$0.17 beat (+6.4%) | **+19%** |\n| Net Income | **$42.1B** | — | — | vs. $36.33B prior year |\n| Gross Margin | **48.2%** | — | — | vs. 46.9% prior year |\n| Operating Cash Flow | **~$54B** | — | — | — |\n\nAll-time record quarter for both revenue and EPS.\n\n---\n\n### 2. Segment Breakdown\n\n| Segment | Revenue | YoY | vs. Estimate |\n|---------|---------|-----|-------------|\n| **iPhone** | $85.27B | **+23.3%** | Beat ($78.65B est.) |\n| **Services** | $30.01B | **+14%** | Slight miss ($30.07B est.) |\n| **Wearables/Home/Accessories** | $11.49B | **-2.2%** | — |\n| **iPad** | $8.60B | **+6.3%** | — |\n| **Mac** | $8.39B | **-6.7%** | Missed estimates |\n\n**Geographic highlights:**\n- **Greater China**: $25.53B (+37.9%) — surged from $18.51B a year ago; all-time record across iPhone, Mac, iPad, and Services in the region\n- Americas: +11.2% | Europe: +12.7% | Japan: +4.7% | Rest of Asia-Pacific: +18.0%\n\n---\n\n### 3. Key Highlights & Surprises\n\n- **iPhone** set its best-ever quarter, with CEO Tim Cook saying \"demand for iPhone was just simply staggering.\" Driven by iPhone 17 (released September 2025).\n- **Services** hit a new all-time high at $30B; installed base surpassed **2.5 billion active devices**.\n- **Greater China surge (+38%)** was the standout upside surprise.\n- **Mac declined 7%** — missed Wall Street expectations; a rare soft spot.\n- **Wearables slipped 2.2%** despite AirPods Pro 3 launching (supply constraints cited).\n- **Tariff impact**: U.S. tariffs cost Apple ~**$1.4B** in Q1.\n- **Supply constraints**: Apple exited the quarter with \"very lean supply\" on advanced 3nm node chips (Apple Silicon); AirPods Pro 3 also constrained.\n- **Shareholder returns**: ~$32B returned (dividends + buybacks); net cash position of $54B ($145B cash, $91B debt). Dividend: $0.26/share payable Feb 12, 2026.\n\n---\n\n### 4. Forward Guidance (Q2 2026 / March Quarter)\n\n| Metric | Guidance | vs. Prior Consensus |\n|--------|----------|---------------------|\n| Revenue growth | **+13% to +16% YoY** | Implies $107.8B–$110.7B vs. $104.84B est. — strong beat |\n| Gross margin | **48%–49%** | — |\n| Services growth | Similar to Q1 (~14%) | — |\n\n- CFO **Kevan Parekh** flagged that **memory prices** had minimal Q1 impact but are \"expected to increase significantly\" in Q2 and beyond.\n- Guidance assumes current global tariff rates remain stable.\n- Supply constraints on advanced nodes remain unresolved; Cook declined to estimate when supply/demand would balance.\n\n---\n\n### 5. Stock Reaction\n\n| Timeframe | Move |\n|-----------|------|\n| After-hours Jan 29 | **+0.72%**, reaching ~$258.08 |\n| Jan 30 (next day) | **+0.46%** |\n| Week following | Muted; broader Nasdaq headwinds |\n| Feb 18, 2026 | ~$265.32, ~10% below the 47-analyst consensus target of $292.15 |\n\nThe reaction was subdued relative to the earnings beat (+/- 3.83% implied move going in). Analysts attributed the muted response to the lack of forward guidance beyond Q2, memory cost concerns, and the stock's valuation already pricing in strong results.\n\n---\n\n### 6. Analyst Commentary\n\n**Bullish / Raised Targets:**\n| Firm | Rating | New PT | Prior PT | Note |\n|------|--------|--------|----------|------|\n| Wedbush | Outperform | $350 | $350 | Maintained; cites AI upgrade cycle |\n| Oppenheimer | Outperform | $340 | $325 | \"AI-related opportunities\" |\n| Citi (Atif Malik) | Buy | $330 | $315 | Accelerating Services + AI monetization |\n| Goldman Sachs | Buy | $330 | — | Improved App Store trends; multi-year constructive |\n| Evercore ISI | Buy | $330 | — | Ecosystem + AI device/services contributions |\n| Morgan Stanley | Overweight | $315 | $305 | High-conviction; Siri relaunch + Apple Intelligence |\n| JPMorgan | Overweight | $315 | $305 | Strong iPhone data |\n| Loop Capital | Buy | $315 | — | Upgraded on iPhone 17 launch strength |\n| Maxim Group | — | $300 | — | Raised Jan 30 |\n\n**Bearish / Cautious:**\n| Firm | Rating | New PT | Prior PT | Note |\n|------|--------|--------|----------|------|\n| Jefferies (Edison Lee) | Hold | $276.47 | $283.36 | Lowered; iPhone surge driven by pricing/promotions, not tech; Services slowdown concerns |\n\n**Consensus**: 77 Wall Street analysts tracked with bullish consensus; median PT ~$300; range $215–$350.\n\n---\n\n### 7. Sector Impact\n\n**TSMC (TSM):**\n- Reported record Q4 2025 results (announced Jan 15, 2026): profit +35% YoY, revenue $33.73B (beat by $400M+).\n- Q1 2026 guidance: $34.6B–$35.8B vs. prior consensus of $32.5B — massive beat driven by Apple AI chip demand.\n- Apple accounts for ~22–25% of TSMC revenue; absolute contribution projected to surpass NT$1 trillion (~$33B) in 2026.\n- Supply constraint story (3nm) mentioned by Apple on earnings call directly validates TSMC's advanced node capacity tightness.\n\n**Broadcom (AVGO):**\n- Reported Q1 2026 earnings beat with guidance above expectations (reported March 4, 2026).\n- CEO Hock Tan cited line-of-sight to **$100B+ in AI chip revenue**.\n- Stock +5% in extended trading on its own report.\n- Broadcom is Apple's custom chip partner (for Apple's C1 modem and other silicon); described by analysts as a \"big winner\" in Apple's AI silicon strategy.\n\n**Qualcomm (QCOM):**\n- Remains iPhone modem supplier (transitioning as Apple's C1 modem, developed with Broadcom, ramps). Apple's strong iPhone demand is broadly positive for Qualcomm near-term, though the multi-year modem transition is a headwind.\n\n**Broader Tech:**\n- Apple's blowout results were a positive signal for the tech sector's hardware demand, partially countering late-2025 concerns about a demand slowdown.\n- The memory price increase warning (DRAM/NAND) had a mixed read-through — negative for Apple margins but a revenue positive for memory makers (Samsung, SK Hynix, Micron).\n\n---\n\nSources:\n- [Apple Reports First Quarter Results — Apple Newsroom](https://www.apple.com/newsroom/2026/01/apple-reports-first-quarter-results/)\n- [Apple Reports Record-Setting 1Q 2026 Results: $42.1B Profit on $143.8B Revenue — MacRumors](https://www.macrumors.com/2026/01/29/apple-1q-2026-earnings/)\n- [Apple (AAPL) Earnings Report Q1 2026 — CNBC](https://www.cnbc.com/2026/01/29/apple-aapl-earnings-report-q1-2026.html)\n- [Apple Analysts Like iPhone Sales Surge but Memory Concerns Linger — CNBC](https://www.cnbc.com/2026/01/30/analysts-like-apples-iphone-sales-surge-but-memory-concerns-linger.html)\n- [Apple Q1 2026 Earnings Call — MacDailyNews Live Notes](https://macdailynews.com/2026/01/29/macdailynews-presents-live-notes-from-apples-q126-conference-call/)\n- [Apple's Q1 2026 Earnings Explained by Tim Cook and CFO Kevan Parekh — MacObserver](https://www.macobserver.com/news/apples-q1-2026-earnings-explained-by-tim-cook-and-cfo-kevan-parekh/)\n- [Apple Stock Forecast: Did Record Q1 2026 Earnings Lift Targets? — Capital.com](https://capital.com/en-int/market-updates/apple-stock-forecast-20-02-2026)\n- [Apple's Best Quarter Ever Delivers $144B — TIKR](https://www.tikr.com/blog/apple-best-quarter-ever-delivers-144b-why-eps-is-forecast-to-grow-14-in-2026)\n- [TSMC Q4 Profit Record — CNBC](https://www.cnbc.com/2026/01/15/tsmc-q4-profit-record-ai-chip-demand-nt1-trillion.html)\n- [Broadcom and TSMC Emerge as 'Big Winners' — Yahoo Finance](https://finance.yahoo.com/news/broadcom-tsmc-emerge-big-winners-140838228.html)\n- [Apple Q1 2026 Earnings Call Transcript — Motley Fool](https://www.fool.com/earnings/call-transcripts/2026/01/29/apple-aapl-q1-2026-earnings-call-transcript/)\n- [Breaking Down Apple's Record Q1 2026 Earnings — WiFi Planet](https://wi-fiplanet.com/breaking-down-apples-record-q1-2026-earnings-key-drivers-and-investor-insights/)" ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/confidence> "1"^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#double> ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/agent_id> "87589578-d92c-441c-9ded-2f9d2facf520" ;
	<http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment> "Here is the comprehensive summary of Apple's fiscal Q1 2026 (calendar Q4 2025) earnings:\n\n---\n\n## Apple Fiscal Q1 2026 Earnings — Comprehensive Summary\n**Reported: January 29, 2026 | Period: October–December 2025**\n\n---\n\n### 1. Financial Results\n\n| Metric | Actual | Analyst Estimate | Beat/Miss | YoY Change |\n|--------|--------|-----------------|-----------|------------|\n| Revenue | **$143.8B** | $138.48B | +$5.3B beat | **+16%** |\n| EPS (diluted) | **$2.84** | $2.67 | +$0.17 beat (+6.4%) | **+19%** |\n| Net Income | **$42.1B** | — | — | vs. $36.33B prior year |\n| Gross Margin | **48.2%** | — | — | vs. 46.9% prior year |\n| Operating Cash Flow | **~$54B** | — | — | — |\n\nAll-time record quarter for both revenue and EPS.\n\n---\n\n### 2. Segment Breakdown\n\n| Segment | Revenue | YoY | vs. Estimate |\n|---------|---------|-----|-------------|\n| **iPhone** | $85.27B | **+23.3%** | Beat ($78.65B est.) |\n| **Services** | $30.01B | **+14%** | Slight miss ($30.07B est.) |\n| **Wearables/Home/Accessories** | $11.49B | **-2.2%** | — |\n| **iPad** | $8.60B | **+6.3%** | — |\n| **Mac** | $8.39B | **-6.7%** | Missed estimates |\n\n**Geographic highlights:**\n- **Greater China**: $25.53B (+37.9%) — surged from $18.51B a year ago; all-time record across iPhone, Mac, iPad, and Services in the region\n- Americas: +11.2% | Europe: +12.7% | Japan: +4.7% | Rest of Asia-Pacific: +18.0%\n\n---\n\n### 3. Key Highlights & Surprises\n\n- **iPhone** set its best-ever quarter, with CEO Tim Cook saying \"demand for iPhone was just simply staggering.\" Driven by iPhone 17 (released September 2025).\n- **Services** hit a new all-time high at $30B; installed base surpassed **2.5 billion active devices**.\n- **Greater China surge (+38%)** was the standout upside surprise.\n- **Mac declined 7%** — missed Wall Street expectations; a rare soft spot.\n- **Wearables slipped 2.2%** despite AirPods Pro 3 launching (supply constraints cited).\n- **Tariff impact**: U.S. tariffs cost Apple ~**$1.4B** in Q1.\n- **Supply constraints**: Apple exited the quarter with \"very lean supply\" on advanced 3nm node chips (Apple Silicon); AirPods Pro 3 also constrained.\n- **Shareholder returns**: ~$32B returned (dividends + buybacks); net cash position of $54B ($145B cash, $91B debt). Dividend: $0.26/share payable Feb 12, 2026.\n\n---\n\n### 4. Forward Guidance (Q2 2026 / March Quarter)\n\n| Metric | Guidance | vs. Prior Consensus |\n|--------|----------|---------------------|\n| Revenue growth | **+13% to +16% YoY** | Implies $107.8B–$110.7B vs. $104.84B est. — strong beat |\n| Gross margin | **48%–49%** | — |\n| Services growth | Similar to Q1 (~14%) | — |\n\n- CFO **Kevan Parekh** flagged that **memory prices** had minimal Q1 impact but are \"expected to increase significantly\" in Q2 and beyond.\n- Guidance assumes current global tariff rates remain stable.\n- Supply constraints on advanced nodes remain unresolved; Cook declined to estimate when supply/demand would balance.\n\n---\n\n### 5. Stock Reaction\n\n| Timeframe | Move |\n|-----------|------|\n| After-hours Jan 29 | **+0.72%**, reaching ~$258.08 |\n| Jan 30 (next day) | **+0.46%** |\n| Week following | Muted; broader Nasdaq headwinds |\n| Feb 18, 2026 | ~$265.32, ~10% below the 47-analyst consensus target of $292.15 |\n\nThe reaction was subdued relative to the earnings beat (+/- 3.83% implied move going in). Analysts attributed the muted response to the lack of forward guidance beyond Q2, memory cost concerns, and the stock's valuation already pricing in strong results.\n\n---\n\n### 6. Analyst Commentary\n\n**Bullish / Raised Targets:**\n| Firm | Rating | New PT | Prior PT | Note |\n|------|--------|--------|----------|------|\n| Wedbush | Outperform | $350 | $350 | Maintained; cites AI upgrade cycle |\n| Oppenheimer | Outperform | $340 | $325 | \"AI-related opportunities\" |\n| Citi (Atif Malik) | Buy | $330 | $315 | Accelerating Services + AI monetization |\n| Goldman Sachs | Buy | $330 | — | Improved App Store trends; multi-year constructive |\n| Evercore ISI | Buy | $330 | — | Ecosystem + AI device/services contributions |\n| Morgan Stanley | Overweight | $315 | $305 | High-conviction; Siri relaunch + Apple Intelligence |\n| JPMorgan | Overweight | $315 | $305 | Strong iPhone data |\n| Loop Capital | Buy | $315 | — | Upgraded on iPhone 17 launch strength |\n| Maxim Group | — | $300 | — | Raised Jan 30 |\n\n**Bearish / Cautious:**\n| Firm | Rating | New PT | Prior PT | Note |\n|------|--------|--------|----------|------|\n| Jefferies (Edison Lee) | Hold | $276.47 | $283.36 | Lowered; iPhone surge driven by pricing/promotions, not tech; Services slowdown concerns |\n\n**Consensus**: 77 Wall Street analysts tracked with bullish consensus; median PT ~$300; range $215–$350.\n\n---\n\n### 7. Sector Impact\n\n**TSMC (TSM):**\n- Reported record Q4 2025 results (announced Jan 15, 2026): profit +35% YoY, revenue $33.73B (beat by $400M+).\n- Q1 2026 guidance: $34.6B–$35.8B vs. prior consensus of $32.5B — massive beat driven by Apple AI chip demand.\n- Apple accounts for ~22–25% of TSMC revenue; absolute contribution projected to surpass NT$1 trillion (~$33B) in 2026.\n- Supply constraint story (3nm) mentioned by Apple on earnings call directly validates TSMC's advanced node capacity tightness.\n\n**Broadcom (AVGO):**\n- Reported Q1 2026 earnings beat with guidance above expectations (reported March 4, 2026).\n- CEO Hock Tan cited line-of-sight to **$100B+ in AI chip revenue**.\n- Stock +5% in extended trading on its own report.\n- Broadcom is Apple's custom chip partner (for Apple's C1 modem and other silicon); described by analysts as a \"big winner\" in Apple's AI silicon strategy.\n\n**Qualcomm (QCOM):**\n- Remains iPhone modem supplier (transitioning as Apple's C1 modem, developed with Broadcom, ramps). Apple's strong iPhone demand is broadly positive for Qualcomm near-term, though the multi-year modem transition is a headwind.\n\n**Broader Tech:**\n- Apple's blowout results were a positive signal for the tech sector's hardware demand, partially countering late-2025 concerns about a demand slowdown.\n- The memory price increase warning (DRAM/NAND) had a mixed read-through — negative for Apple margins but a revenue positive for memory makers (Samsung, SK Hynix, Micron).\n\n---\n\nSources:\n- [Apple Reports First Quarter Results — Apple Newsroom](https://www.apple.com/newsroom/2026/01/apple-reports-first-quarter-results/)\n- [Apple Reports Record-Setting 1Q 2026 Results: $42.1B Profit on $143.8B Revenue — MacRumors](https://www.macrumors.com/2026/01/29/apple-1q-2026-earnings/)\n- [Apple (AAPL) Earnings Report Q1 2026 — CNBC](https://www.cnbc.com/2026/01/29/apple-aapl-earnings-report-q1-2026.html)\n- [Apple Analysts Like iPhone Sales Surge but Memory Concerns Linger — CNBC](https://www.cnbc.com/2026/01/30/analysts-like-apples-iphone-sales-surge-but-memory-concerns-linger.html)\n- [Apple Q1 2026 Earnings Call — MacDailyNews Live Notes](https://macdailynews.com/2026/01/29/macdailynews-presents-live-notes-from-apples-q126-conference-call/)\n- [Apple's Q1 2026 Earnings Explained by Tim Cook and CFO Kevan Parekh — MacObserver](https://www.macobserver.com/news/apples-q1-2026-earnings-explained-by-tim-cook-and-cfo-kevan-parekh/)\n- [Apple Stock Forecast: Did Record Q1 2026 Earnings Lift Targets? — Capital.com](https://capital.com/en-int/market-updates/apple-stock-forecast-20-02-2026)\n- [Apple's Best Quarter Ever Delivers $144B — TIKR](https://www.tikr.com/blog/apple-best-quarter-ever-delivers-144b-why-eps-is-forecast-to-grow-14-in-2026)\n- [TSMC Q4 Profit Record — CNBC](https://www.cnbc.com/2026/01/15/tsmc-q4-profit-record-ai-chip-demand-nt1-trillion.html)\n- [Broadcom and TSMC Emerge as 'Big Winners' — Yahoo Finance](https://finance.yahoo.com/news/broadcom-tsmc-emerge-big-winners-140838228.html)\n- [Apple Q1 2026 Earnings Call Transcript — Motley Fool](https://www.fool.com/earnings/call-transcripts/2026/01/29/apple-aapl-q1-2026-earnings-call-transcript/)\n- [Breaking Down Apple's Record Q1 2026 Earnings — WiFi Planet](https://wi-fiplanet.com/breaking-down-apples-record-q1-2026-earnings-key-drivers-and-investor-insights/)" ;
	<http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "[researcher] Here is the comprehensive summary of Apple's fiscal Q1 2026 (calendar Q4 2025) e" ;
	a <https://schema.org/EpisodicMemory> .


# === memory-4a4b0851-3d55-4168-aa27-0b4cb2419b32 ===
<urn:tesserai:twin:memory-4a4b0851-3d55-4168-aa27-0b4cb2419b32> <http://tesserai.io/ontology/createdAt> "2026-03-25T00:44:40.682081Z"^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#dateTime> ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/topics> "[\"Write Correlations and Executive Summary\",\"Write correlations.md\",\"coder\"]" ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/tool_name> "coder" ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/structured_data> "null" ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/run_id> "0c528c09-a4f4-4c47-b84d-8539960a4582" ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/memory_type> "episodic" ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/created_at> "2026-03-25T00:44:40.681257+00:00" ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/content> "Created `analysis/correlations.md`. Here's a summary of what's in it:\n\n**Structure & key data points:**\n\n- **Overview** — frames the ~$490B combined quarterly revenue and staggered reporting window\n- **Revenue & Growth** — comparison table of all four companies; identifies the two-speed growth split (Microsoft/Alphabet at 14–16% vs. Apple/Amazon at 4–10%); documents universal operating margin expansion\n- **AI Investment Convergence** — $255B+ in combined 2026 CapEx commitments; CEO quotes; monetization maturity ranking (Microsoft most mature at ~$13B ARR, Apple least quantified)\n- **Cloud Wars Scorecard** — direct AWS/Azure/Google Cloud table with AI contribution percentages, operating margins, market share, and guidance; explains Azure's 15-pp growth rate advantage over AWS as the cycle's most consequential competitive development\n- **Advertising Market Signals** — Google + Amazon's combined $101B ad quarter; documents the refutation of the AI-cannibalizes-search thesis with hard data; CTV structural shift analysis\n- **Supply Chain & Semiconductors** — TSMC as a single-point-of-failure across Apple (A19), NVIDIA (Blackwell), and AMD (MI300X); Broadcom's dual consumer/hyperscaler exposure; the custom silicon displacement trajectory\n- **Earnings Surprise Patterns** — every company beat both revenue and EPS; the \"large beat + conservative guide\" pattern dissected; Amazon's $4B wide operating income range explained as depreciation-timing transparency\n- **Market Reaction Divergences** — the \"guidance tax\" on Apple vs. Microsoft; how Alphabet's below-consensus Q1 guide was overwhelmed by Cloud margin; why Amazon's below-prior-year op. income guide was ignored\n- **7 Key Takeaways** — each backed by specific data, covering AI margin accretion, the CapEx arms race scale, the Azure/AWS gap, advertising health, Apple's indirect flywheel, TSMC concentration risk, and the institutionalized conservative guidance behavior" ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/confidence> "1"^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#double> ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/agent_id> "cc9f5d6e-b6ce-448f-9a31-246205e98a8a" ;
	<http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment> "Created `analysis/correlations.md`. Here's a summary of what's in it:\n\n**Structure & key data points:**\n\n- **Overview** — frames the ~$490B combined quarterly revenue and staggered reporting window\n- **Revenue & Growth** — comparison table of all four companies; identifies the two-speed growth split (Microsoft/Alphabet at 14–16% vs. Apple/Amazon at 4–10%); documents universal operating margin expansion\n- **AI Investment Convergence** — $255B+ in combined 2026 CapEx commitments; CEO quotes; monetization maturity ranking (Microsoft most mature at ~$13B ARR, Apple least quantified)\n- **Cloud Wars Scorecard** — direct AWS/Azure/Google Cloud table with AI contribution percentages, operating margins, market share, and guidance; explains Azure's 15-pp growth rate advantage over AWS as the cycle's most consequential competitive development\n- **Advertising Market Signals** — Google + Amazon's combined $101B ad quarter; documents the refutation of the AI-cannibalizes-search thesis with hard data; CTV structural shift analysis\n- **Supply Chain & Semiconductors** — TSMC as a single-point-of-failure across Apple (A19), NVIDIA (Blackwell), and AMD (MI300X); Broadcom's dual consumer/hyperscaler exposure; the custom silicon displacement trajectory\n- **Earnings Surprise Patterns** — every company beat both revenue and EPS; the \"large beat + conservative guide\" pattern dissected; Amazon's $4B wide operating income range explained as depreciation-timing transparency\n- **Market Reaction Divergences** — the \"guidance tax\" on Apple vs. Microsoft; how Alphabet's below-consensus Q1 guide was overwhelmed by Cloud margin; why Amazon's below-prior-year op. income guide was ignored\n- **7 Key Takeaways** — each backed by specific data, covering AI margin accretion, the CapEx arms race scale, the Azure/AWS gap, advertising health, Apple's indirect flywheel, TSMC concentration risk, and the institutionalized conservative guidance behavior" ;
	<http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "[coder] Created `analysis/correlations.md`. Here's a summary of what's in it:\n\n**Structu" ;
	a <https://schema.org/EpisodicMemory> .


